Scott: Little dudes, are they technically workers, farmers, peasants?

429
00:23:07,660 --> 00:23:09,120
Rym: BoardGameGeep calls them meeples.

430
00:23:09,680 --> 00:23:10,057
Scott: Meeples?

431
00:23:10,522 --> 00:23:11,217
Rym: I'm not sure why.

432
00:23:11,420 --> 00:23:14,420
Scott: I think that's the generic name for wooden pieces of that shape.

433
00:23:14,784 --> 00:23:15,018
Rym: Yeah.

434
00:23:15,460 --> 00:23:18,260
Scott: But that's not their thematic meaning in the theme of Carcassonne.

435
00:23:18,260 --> 00:23:22,080
Rym: I've noticed that we almost never talk about the theme of a game, so it really doesn't matter.

436
00:23:22,140 --> 00:23:25,040
Rym: The theme of the game is you're building little towns in the countryside of France.

437
00:23:25,500 --> 00:23:25,626
Scott: Hooray!

438
00:23:26,001 --> 00:23:26,370
Rym: That's it.

439
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:27,156
Rym: Friends.

440
00:23:27,720 --> 00:23:28,101
Rym: But that's it.

441
00:23:28,181 --> 00:23:29,164
Rym: The game is so simple.

442
00:23:29,384 --> 00:23:30,668
Rym: You draw a tile, you look at it.

443
00:23:31,049 --> 00:23:35,480
Rym: You show it to everyone around the table, because the rules even say specifically you must show the tile to everyone.

444
00:23:35,860 --> 00:23:38,320
Scott: So that everyone can suggest where to put it.

445
00:23:38,520 --> 00:23:41,460
Rym: Yes, I believe the exact words are so that they can advise.

446
00:23:42,400 --> 00:23:42,669
Rym: Mm-hmm.

447
00:23:43,481 --> 00:23:45,452
Rym: Usually the advice is, "Hey, put it on my

448
00:23:45,512 --> 00:23:45,774
Rym: city.".

449
00:23:45,834 --> 00:23:46,820
Rym: No, put it on my city!

450
00:23:47,140 --> 00:23:47,745
Scott: Put it somewhere.

451
00:23:47,806 --> 00:23:49,520
Scott: that helps me and screws you over.

452
00:23:49,940 --> 00:23:50,070
Rym: Yeah.

453
00:23:51,604 --> 00:23:51,879
Scott: Awesome.

454
00:23:52,362 --> 00:23:52,803
Rym: But that's it.

455
00:23:52,843 --> 00:23:57,017
Rym: You draw a tile, you place the tile, you put a dude on it or not put a dude on it.

456
00:23:57,398 --> 00:23:57,760
Rym: That's it.

457
00:23:58,181 --> 00:24:01,820
Rym: And you go around until all the tiles have been placed, and then you do the final scoring.

458
00:24:02,300 --> 00:24:07,220
Scott: Now the way to score big points is when you put a dude on the board, there are four places you can put him.

459
00:24:07,800 --> 00:24:09,780
Scott: You can put him, well, in the basic game.

460
00:24:10,220 --> 00:24:11,264
Scott: You can put him on a road.

461
00:24:11,384 --> 00:24:15,880
Scott: If you put him on a road, you want that road to be really long, because then you get a lot of points.

462
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:16,502
Scott: Yep.

463
00:24:16,542 --> 00:24:22,600
Rym: Basically, you put guys on the board, and with one exception, whenever the thing they're on finishes and scores, you get the dude back.

464
00:24:22,780 --> 00:24:23,939
Rym: Because you have a limited number of dudes.

465
00:24:24,140 --> 00:24:28,376
Scott: So let's say a road is ten tiles long, and I have a guy on that road.

466
00:24:28,537 --> 00:24:29,340
Scott: I get ten points.

467
00:24:29,640 --> 00:24:32,535
Scott: Let's say the road is ten tiles long, and Rym has a guy on the road.

468
00:24:32,575 --> 00:24:33,400
Scott: He gets ten points.

469
00:24:34,060 --> 00:24:35,480
Scott: You can also put guys in castles.

470
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:43,400
Scott: And the castles, when the castle is sealed up and the castle can't possibly expand anymore, you see how many tiles the castle is.

471
00:24:43,902 --> 00:24:47,700
Scott: So if I make a five tile castle, I would get ten points.

472
00:24:48,202 --> 00:24:50,999
Scott: If there were little shields in the castle, I would get more points than that.

473
00:24:51,381 --> 00:24:52,316
Scott: You know, that's how it is.

474
00:24:53,602 --> 00:24:55,580
Scott: Putting guys in the grass is weird.

475
00:24:56,140 --> 00:25:00,140
Scott: Putting guys in the little churches, the cloisters, is also a little weird.

476
00:25:00,341 --> 00:25:04,380
Scott: But a cloister can get you anywhere from one to nine points if you put a guy in it.

477
00:25:04,660 --> 00:25:12,340
Rym: Yeah, basically it's just a game of placing your guys in an optimal way so as to get victory points from buildings and roads and such that finish.

478
00:25:13,061 --> 00:25:21,800
Rym: And you get some consolation points at the end of the game for things that didn't finish, but you're mostly screwed at that point because you had a guy who was on the board instead of being useful doing nothing.

479
00:25:22,140 --> 00:25:24,271
Scott: You have a limited number of little guys, I think.

480
00:25:24,432 --> 00:25:25,276
Scott: Like, nine.

481
00:25:25,497 --> 00:25:26,000
Scott: Not so many.

482
00:25:26,180 --> 00:25:26,507
Rym: Not even.

483
00:25:26,630 --> 00:25:27,059
Rym: Like, seven.

484
00:25:27,920 --> 00:25:30,912
Scott: It's not a lot of guys, especially if you don't have any expansions.

485
00:25:31,113 --> 00:25:31,334
Scott: Oi!

486
00:25:31,876 --> 00:25:32,840
Scott: You know, you're screwed.

487
00:25:33,260 --> 00:25:39,460
Scott: So you have to really, you know, be really discerning about where you put your guys on the board.

488
00:25:39,881 --> 00:25:45,600
Scott: If you put them out just on every single tile you put down, you're gonna run out of guys and miss scoring opportunities.

489
00:25:46,501 --> 00:25:49,320
Scott: And if you don't put out enough, well you're not gonna score any points.

490
00:25:49,941 --> 00:25:53,660
Scott: So you have to really put them in the most optimal places you possibly can.

491
00:25:54,020 --> 00:25:54,140
Rym: Yep.

492
00:25:54,582 --> 00:25:59,760
Rym: And I mean, they're all the places you can put guys that are normal and then whenever whatever it is finishes, you get the points back.

493
00:26:00,320 --> 00:26:03,060
Rym: But then you can put them on the grass, which is a farmer.

494
00:26:03,481 --> 00:26:12,040
Rym: And to put it really simply, any cities that are completed at the end of the game are scored based on who has the most farmers touching them.

495
00:26:13,123 --> 00:26:15,219
Rym: And you get a bunch of points, I think four for each one.

496
00:26:16,500 --> 00:26:22,720
Scott: Yeah, so one giant field of grass that all connects and isn't blocked off by roads or castles is a field of grass.

497
00:26:23,480 --> 00:26:29,858
Scott: And you look in that field of grass and you say, "How many completed castles, separate castles, are touching this field of

498
00:26:29,898 --> 00:26:30,199
Scott: grass?".

499
00:26:31,002 --> 00:26:33,760
Scott: Let's say there's three completed castles touching the field of grass.

500
00:26:34,881 --> 00:26:37,019
Scott: Oh, well I have a farmer in that field of grass.

501
00:26:37,580 --> 00:26:41,100
Scott: So I get four points for three castles, twelve points at the end of the game.

502
00:26:41,960 --> 00:26:49,520
Rym: Of course the trade-off is, you put guys in the farm where you now don't get them back and they sit there doing nothing for the entire game until the very very end.

503
00:26:50,040 --> 00:26:56,160
Scott: Yeah, putting guys in the farm is kind of troublesome too because other people will throw guys in other farms or the same farm.

504
00:26:56,541 --> 00:27:04,080
Scott: Or they'll sneak other farmers into your farm and beat you out, making your farmer useless, which means now you have guys on the board that aren't doing anything and you can't get them back.

505
00:27:05,080 --> 00:27:10,920
Rym: Now the only other mechanics to the game are that there are cases of ties, and basically if there's a tie, everyone wins.

506
00:27:12,201 --> 00:27:17,539
Rym: And the other rule is that you cannot put a guy on a thing that already has a guy in it.

507
00:27:18,420 --> 00:27:20,948
Rym: Now you might wonder, "Alright, then how could I ever tie someone?

508
00:27:21,209 --> 00:27:24,519
Rym: If I have a guy on a road, there's no way you could ever put your guy on the

509
00:27:24,559 --> 00:27:24,700
Rym: road.".

510
00:27:24,861 --> 00:27:27,500
Scott: Well, I just put my guy on a different road and I connect the two roads.

511
00:27:27,940 --> 00:27:36,000
Rym: Yep, so say I got a long road, and then it turns to the right, and then there's a space, and then someone else puts a straight road tile down and puts their guy on it.

512
00:27:36,480 --> 00:27:41,477
Rym: And then the next round he goes, he puts another straight tile to the left of that one, and now the two roads are connected.

513
00:27:41,517 --> 00:27:42,380
Rym: Now we're sharing the points.

514
00:27:43,181 --> 00:27:46,080
Rym: If he somehow got two guys on that road, he gets all the points and I get Dick.

515
00:27:46,820 --> 00:27:48,705
Scott: That's how the farmers work also.

516
00:27:48,746 --> 00:27:54,883
Scott: You have some grass and some other grass, a guy puts a farmer in the second grass, connects the two grasses to make one grass, and woah!

517
00:27:55,525 --> 00:27:56,588
Scott: Castles the same way, too.

518
00:27:56,969 --> 00:28:00,700
Scott: Two castles, a guy in each, castles connect, now it's one castle, the end.

519
00:28:01,281 --> 00:28:04,634
Rym: Now, that sounds very simple, and it's true.

520
00:28:04,714 --> 00:28:06,220
Rym: The game is incredibly simple.

521
00:28:06,320 --> 00:28:09,700
Scott: I mean, they sell this game in Toys R Us, that's why it's so simple.

522
00:28:09,940 --> 00:28:13,448
Rym: I mean, it's very easy to learn, but don't underestimate this game.

523
00:28:13,528 --> 00:28:19,320
Rym: It is not a light or easy game, it is not a limited game, there are many possibilities.

524
00:28:20,641 --> 00:28:23,815
Rym: In terms of tactics versus strategy, I'd say it's pretty much 100% tactics.

525
00:28:25,720 --> 00:28:31,879
Scott: Yeah, you really can't go into the game thinking, "I'm gonna build a big castle," or "I'm gonna try to get a whole bunch of long

526
00:28:31,959 --> 00:28:32,140
Scott: roads.".

527
00:28:32,200 --> 00:28:32,842
Scott: That doesn't work.

528
00:28:33,323 --> 00:28:35,589
Scott: It's a lot of randomness in what tiles you draw.

529
00:28:35,629 --> 00:28:47,396
Scott: You pretty much have to draw tiles, and at the moment you draw the tile, put it in the optimum position to either get the most points for you, or take the most points away from other people.

530
00:28:47,436 --> 00:28:54,340
Scott: if you can't get points for you with the tile, and then optimally put your guys out on the tiles you draw to get the most points for you.

531
00:28:54,820 --> 00:29:07,138
Rym: Now, you also might think, "Hey, if all you ever get to do is draw a random tile and put it down, you can only put your guys on those random tiles, couldn't you get dicked by the tiles, and wouldn't the tile drawing really affect the

532
00:29:07,158 --> 00:29:07,419
Rym: game?".

533
00:29:07,824 --> 00:29:08,939
Scott: It kinda does, a little bit.

534
00:29:09,220 --> 00:29:12,328
Rym: The answer is really no, because I always win.

535
00:29:12,348 --> 00:29:24,780
Rym: I win every time we play, and I've played a lot of games of this, and the fact that one person can consistently do very well despite the randomness of the tiles means that the tactics mean a lot more than what you draw.

536
00:29:25,500 --> 00:29:28,831
Scott: Yeah, what you draw can mean something.

537
00:29:28,851 --> 00:29:31,620
Scott: if you play in a certain way.

538
00:29:32,041 --> 00:29:41,580
Scott: Like, if you play to build a giant castle, then the game might come down to whether you draw a certain tile that can finish the castle or not.

539
00:29:42,120 --> 00:29:45,780
Scott: However, that's only in like a one-game basis.

540
00:29:46,180 --> 00:29:57,005
Scott: Overall, from game to game, playing with a better strategy, usually a strategy that doesn't depend on getting specific tiles, will win you the game more often.

541
00:29:57,065 --> 00:30:11,840
Scott: So while someone might play in a certain way and then win or lose based on the draw of the tiles, overall, the way to win the most games over the course of your life is to play better than that and not depend on the tiles you draw.

542
00:30:12,420 --> 00:30:15,980
Rym: Very enlightening, but how come you can never win since you seem to understand that so well?

543
00:30:16,340 --> 00:30:18,460
Scott: Because that's the only part of it I understand, it's not enough.

544
00:30:19,802 --> 00:30:24,620
Rym: I mean, the neat thing is that the game's very simple, but there are a lot of things you can do.

545
00:30:24,800 --> 00:30:28,439
Rym: Like, you can't really screw someone other than maybe taking points away from them.

546
00:30:29,040 --> 00:30:36,060
Rym: But because the nature of the tiles and the fact that you have to place tiles in a legal manner, you know, roads touch roads, grass touches grass.

547
00:30:37,060 --> 00:30:44,680
Rym: If the other person, or say you're playing with a bunch of people and one person is building this massive city and it's huge, it's gonna score them a ton of points and probably win in the game.

548
00:30:45,640 --> 00:30:54,060
Rym: You can just put roads and other cities around it in such a way that they'll need a really, really rare or possibly non-existent piece to finish their city.

549
00:30:54,540 --> 00:30:56,999
Rym: Now it's guaranteed the city won't finish, you don't have to worry about it.

550
00:30:57,300 --> 00:31:04,395
Scott: Yeah, in the regular old game of Carcassonne with no expansion packs, there are a lot of ways that you can make it so.

551
00:31:04,555 --> 00:31:10,020
Scott: a city can't be finished or a road can't be finished because there is no such piece that fits in that spot.

552
00:31:10,220 --> 00:31:10,361
Scott: So

553
00:31:10,401 --> 00:31:23,760
Rym: in normal Carcassonne, unless a bunch of players team up to all of them finish a city together to basically push everyone else out of the game, anyone who tries to build a city that's more than a couple of tiles is gonna get dicked by everyone else just sticking roads in the way.

554
00:31:24,420 --> 00:31:29,920
Scott: Yeah, a four or five city is like the biggest one you can expect to build by yourself in the long run.

555
00:31:30,140 --> 00:31:32,879
Scott: And even then, you're probably better off building three or fours.

556
00:31:33,080 --> 00:31:35,980
Rym: Yeah, in original Settlers, or Settlers, god, Carcassonne.

557
00:31:36,340 --> 00:31:37,239
Scott: Yeah, Carcassonne.

558
00:31:37,561 --> 00:31:42,300
Rym: Now, that's it, and I love the game, but we're gonna go over all the expansions because... Well, not all the expansions.

559
00:31:42,320 --> 00:31:44,660
Rym: All the expansions that we have and/or care about.

560
00:31:44,900 --> 00:31:47,880
Scott: Right, now here's the thing, people talk a lot about Carcassonization.

561
00:31:49,220 --> 00:31:55,620
Scott: Basically, what they've done, the company that publishes Carcassonne, I don't know who it is, I forget, I think it's Rio Grande, don't quote me on that.

562
00:31:55,901 --> 00:31:57,220
Rym: Uh-huh-huh, Incorporated.

563
00:31:57,460 --> 00:32:06,340
Scott: Yeah, what they've done is they've taken a whole lot of other German games or European board games and they've put the Carcassonne label on them.

564
00:32:06,400 --> 00:32:23,020
Scott: Because Carcassonne was so successful and popular that it sold in Toys R Us even, they figured that they can take other similar tile-laying guy-placing games, slap a Carcassonne label on them, changing the original name of the game, and get a bunch of sales because there's Carcassonne on it.

565
00:32:23,300 --> 00:32:26,011
Rym: And a lot of the games are good, but they're not really what we're talking about.

566
00:32:26,071 --> 00:32:28,240
Rym: These are expansions that basically make it a different game.

567
00:32:28,240 --> 00:32:40,840
Scott: Yeah, they also, what they've done is make a bunch of expansion packs, which include tiles and extra wooden pieces that you can add to the game of Carcassonne to put new rules and situations into it.

568
00:32:41,220 --> 00:32:44,300
Scott: And those are the expansion packs we're going to talk about, at least some of the ones we've played.

569
00:32:44,500 --> 00:32:49,540
Rym: Yes, now two of the three are very good and I highly recommend them, but the first one we're going to talk about sucks.

570
00:32:50,201 --> 00:33:00,040
Rym: Now the only other thing I'll say is that when it comes to the expansions, if you buy Carcassonne, I'd highly recommend you play it a whole bunch of times without the expansions before you add them in.

571
00:33:00,480 --> 00:33:03,231
Scott: Yeah, the expansions aren't to make the game playable.

572
00:33:03,271 --> 00:33:05,580
Scott: The game is great and playable all on its own.

573
00:33:06,060 --> 00:33:11,660
Scott: The reason to get the expansion is because you've played the original game so much that you need to add some flavor.

574
00:33:11,800 --> 00:33:17,451
Scott: And then when you've played the game out with that expansion, get another expansion, and so on.

575
00:33:17,871 --> 00:33:22,480
Scott: Some of the expansions, though, are not so good, I've heard, but I'm only going to talk about the ones I've played.

576
00:33:22,840 --> 00:33:26,348
Rym: Yep, and the ones we've played are all fantastic, except for The River.

577
00:33:26,368 --> 00:33:31,180
Rym: Now most Carcassonne boxes now come with The River in the box already.

578
00:33:31,260 --> 00:33:36,008
Scott: Well, The River was the very first expansion, I think, and I think there's a River 2.

579
00:33:36,008 --> 00:33:43,120
Scott: I'm not sure if they come with The River 2 now, or, I don't know, but I don't think The River 2 can be that much better than The River 1.

580
00:33:43,120 --> 00:33:44,523
Rym: Yeah, The River's kinda crap.

581
00:33:44,663 --> 00:33:54,460
Rym: All it does is, for the first bit of the game, because normally one tile starts out on the table, and it's always the same tile, and then you take turns drawing and randomly placing.

582
00:33:55,080 --> 00:34:01,393
Rym: In The River, before you draw the random tiles, first every round people draw a random tile from the river stack.

583
00:34:01,773 --> 00:34:04,980
Rym: So the game starts with this long river, and then people build off the sides of it.

584
00:34:05,700 --> 00:34:09,900
Scott: Yep, so game usually starts with one tile and now starts with a big long river.

585
00:34:11,021 --> 00:34:18,179
Rym: Now, it was cool maybe once or twice, but it really just makes the game more limited and takes away some of the tactical decisions.

586
00:34:19,280 --> 00:34:29,120
Scott: Yeah, when the whole board is constructed by people, you know, well, very constructed by people in a mostly random fashion, you really get all sorts of interesting things built.

587
00:34:29,540 --> 00:34:35,560
Scott: When you always start the game with The River, every game with The River starts to look just like the last game with The River.

588
00:34:35,900 --> 00:34:39,347
Rym: I mean, the only real use I can see for The River is to break yourselves out of a rut.

589
00:34:39,648 --> 00:34:46,199
Rym: If you've been playing the same game of Carcassonne over and over again because of the way people play, The River will break you up because you can't do what you expect.

590
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:50,960
Scott: Of course, there are some strategies at The River that make the game really poor.

591
00:34:51,219 --> 00:34:56,500
Rym: Oh yeah, like, when I played The River the first time, I just farmed my ass off and won the game by a bajillion.

592
00:34:56,841 --> 00:34:58,508
Scott: Yep, 'cause see, what happens with?

593
00:34:58,528 --> 00:35:01,520
Scott: The River is adjacent to the water is a whole bunch of grass.

594
00:35:02,560 --> 00:35:14,160
Scott: So you just put farmers in that grass, and now you've got this big U-shaped piece of grass that's gonna have a shit ton of cities adjacent to it when you build the game, and a whole bunch of points.

595
00:35:14,620 --> 00:35:17,480
Scott: So pretty much whoever farms The River the best is probably gonna win.

596
00:35:18,401 --> 00:35:20,680
Rym: Yeah, so I would really not worry about The River.

597
00:35:21,161 --> 00:35:22,563
Scott: Play with The River once or twice.

598
00:35:22,683 --> 00:35:35,400
Scott: once you learn how to play Carcassonne, see how it goes, you know, if people are dumb, and they don't realize that you've farmed The River to win, then I guess it can make an interesting game because no one will just win right away with it.

599
00:35:35,600 --> 00:35:38,500
Rym: Well then you'll win right away because you listen to GeekNights and you know.

600
00:35:39,249 --> 00:35:39,760
Scott: Ah, ah, ah.

601
00:35:40,840 --> 00:35:43,306
Rym: Alright, now the first real expansion we bought.

602
00:35:43,647 --> 00:35:49,140
Rym: that, in my opinion, makes the game awesome, like it took an awesome game and made it more awesome.

603
00:35:49,424 --> 00:35:49,698
Scott: Oh yeah.

604
00:35:50,044 --> 00:35:51,119
Rym: Inns and cathedrals.

605
00:35:51,700 --> 00:35:51,829
Scott: Mm-hmm.

606
00:35:52,260 --> 00:35:57,380
Rym: Now the one thing it adds, in addition to, it adds some special rules, is it adds an extra player.

607
00:35:57,940 --> 00:35:59,120
Rym: You can now play with one more person.

608
00:35:59,180 --> 00:36:02,440
Scott: Carcassonne I think is only a maximum of six players, two to six?

609
00:36:02,902 --> 00:36:03,658
Rym: Uh, it's five players.

610
00:36:04,100 --> 00:36:04,578
Scott: Two to five?

611
00:36:04,941 --> 00:36:07,299
Scott: And the inns and cathedrals allows you to play two to six.

612
00:36:07,700 --> 00:36:07,769
Rym: Yep.

613
00:36:08,261 --> 00:36:10,180
Rym: Now it also adds a big dude.

614
00:36:10,400 --> 00:36:12,579
Rym: So you got all your little dudes, now you have a big dude.

615
00:36:12,900 --> 00:36:16,880
Rym: He counts as two dudes when it comes to breaking ties, but other than that he's just a normal dude.

616
00:36:17,121 --> 00:36:22,500
Scott: Yeah, so when you're gonna invade someone else's farm for like a jillion points, throw your big dude down there.

617
00:36:22,961 --> 00:36:25,339
Scott: Ho ho, now you're gonna get that farm right out of him.

618
00:36:25,720 --> 00:36:29,980
Rym: Yep, of course, if you put him in a crappy farm, now your big dude's out of the game and you're just kinda dicked.

619
00:36:30,600 --> 00:36:30,778
Scott: Yep.

620
00:36:31,201 --> 00:36:33,979
Scott: Well, it adds an element of strategy, just like Tikal has the big dude.

621
00:36:34,320 --> 00:36:40,020
Rym: Now it also adds a whole bunch of tiles that are shaped weirdly and weren't in the first Carcassonne.

622
00:36:40,801 --> 00:36:46,700
Rym: So now, you won't have those cities that never finish because there's a weird piece that has like two cities and then a road and a plane on them.

623
00:36:47,280 --> 00:36:55,560
Scott: But what inevitably happens is those weird tiles come out at the beginning of the game and then you never draw them when you need them to finish the crazy city.

624
00:36:55,960 --> 00:37:04,740
Rym: Yeah, but even so, just having those tiles there makes a lot more things finish and you can't expect to dick someone by sticking a road in their way because they'll find the piece they need.

625
00:37:05,840 --> 00:37:23,960
Scott: Well, they're really necessary in a six player game because if you don't have tiles like that, no one's gonna be able to finish anything because you get one sixth of the tiles that are out there to place and it's really not enough to actually score a significant number of points.

626
00:37:24,660 --> 00:37:30,140
Rym: Now I note that most of what inns and cathedrals adds to Carcassonne has nothing to do with either inns or cathedrals.

627
00:37:30,841 --> 00:37:34,500
Rym: The inns and cathedrals themselves are kinda lame and they're just kinda tacked on.

628
00:37:34,881 --> 00:37:37,813
Scott: Yeah, well, let's talk about the cathedrals because they're like the obvious.

629
00:37:37,974 --> 00:37:39,460
Scott: I think there's three of them?

630
00:37:39,822 --> 00:37:40,176
Rym: Only two.

631
00:37:40,620 --> 00:37:40,762
Scott: Two?

632
00:37:40,782 --> 00:37:41,999
Scott: I thought there were three.

633
00:37:42,926 --> 00:37:43,459
Rym: There's only two.

634
00:37:43,800 --> 00:37:44,038
Rym: Okay.

635
00:37:44,220 --> 00:37:48,220
Rym: They're a big city piece, meaning it's city on all sides, just a big city.

636
00:37:48,420 --> 00:37:51,367
Scott: Yep, there was never a tile like that in the original Carcassonne.

637
00:37:51,928 --> 00:37:54,535
Scott: So this tile is just all city.

638
00:37:54,795 --> 00:37:56,860
Scott: The only place you can put it is in the middle of a city.

639
00:37:57,600 --> 00:38:02,520
Scott: That means if you put this in a city, it becomes incredibly difficult to finish that city.

640
00:38:02,801 --> 00:38:07,240
Rym: It makes every tile in the city worth an extra point, which is huge.

641
00:38:07,920 --> 00:38:12,300
Scott: Yeah, if you finish a city that has a cathedral in it, you're gonna get a shit ton of points.

642
00:38:12,960 --> 00:38:22,438
Rym: Now, the drawback of the cathedral is that normally if the game ends and you have a big city that didn't finish, you get half the number of points you would have gotten if it had finished.

643
00:38:22,478 --> 00:38:23,540
Rym: Kind of a consolation prize.

644
00:38:24,481 --> 00:38:26,172
Rym: If there's a cathedral in there, you don't get anything.

645
00:38:26,716 --> 00:38:27,360
Rym: It's all or nothing.

646
00:38:27,901 --> 00:38:28,943
Scott: It's like a big gamble.

647
00:38:29,044 --> 00:38:36,380
Scott: If you put a cathedral in your own city, then you basically spend the rest of the game trying to finish it to get a shit ton of points and win.

648
00:38:36,900 --> 00:38:46,360
Scott: The more common strategy is to throw the cathedral in someone else's city, because then they have this guy stuck in the city and he's never gonna finish the city because it's impossible.

649
00:38:46,680 --> 00:38:48,899
Rym: And if he gets close, everyone will just keep trying to dick him.

650
00:38:49,380 --> 00:39:07,620
Scott: Yeah, if he gets close to finishing the city, then other people will either jump into the city to get a share of the points, or they'll put roads and stuff in the way to prevent the city from ever finishing, and now he's spent all his tiles making one big city instead of making another city somewhere else that actually could have finished.

651
00:39:08,680 --> 00:39:10,688
Rym: Now, the inns do the exact same thing.

652
00:39:10,708 --> 00:39:13,800
Rym: the cathedral does, only to a road, and there are a lot of them.

653
00:39:13,980 --> 00:39:14,982
Scott: Yeah, there's a lot of inns.

654
00:39:15,163 --> 00:39:18,550
Scott: So if you put an inn, it's just a little symbol next to a road.

655
00:39:18,630 --> 00:39:23,319
Scott: So let's say I'm making a road, and then I add another road to it that has an inn on it.

656
00:39:24,540 --> 00:39:29,492
Scott: The inn makes the whole road double in points, but if the road doesn't ever finish, I get zero points.

657
00:39:29,652 --> 00:39:32,419
Scott: Usually if a road doesn't finish, you still get a bunch of points for it.

658
00:39:34,621 --> 00:39:37,388
Scott: So, you know, no one ever puts an inn on someone else's road.

659
00:39:37,488 --> 00:39:42,460
Scott: Everyone puts an inn on their own road, and then they try to finish it, and other people try to prevent that road from finishing.

660
00:39:43,507 --> 00:39:44,259
Scott: If it's too long.

661
00:39:45,780 --> 00:39:46,175
Rym: And that's it.

662
00:39:46,820 --> 00:39:48,342
Scott: That's all Inns and Cathedrals does.

663
00:39:48,362 --> 00:40:00,340
Scott: It improves the game a great deal, but make sure you're the master of regular Carcassonne before you use it, because you'll ruin a whole bunch of normal Carcassonne games if you start playing with Inns and Cathedrals right away.

664
00:40:00,560 --> 00:40:00,758
Rym: Yeah.

665
00:40:02,060 --> 00:40:05,400
Rym: Now, last and not least, and newest, is the tower.

666
00:40:06,401 --> 00:40:09,300
Scott: The first thing you gotta know about the tower is it comes with this tower.

667
00:40:09,923 --> 00:40:12,477
Rym: You can put all the tiles in it stacked up real nice.

668
00:40:12,517 --> 00:40:13,020
Rym: It's kinda cool.

669
00:40:13,440 --> 00:40:21,220
Scott: Yeah, if you don't have this tower, then you play Carcassonne usually with all the tiles in a big pile, or just stacks on the table all around.

670
00:40:21,680 --> 00:40:23,465
Scott: And it's not really clean or good looking.

671
00:40:23,505 --> 00:40:28,500
Scott: It's like you make a big mess, and then you build the game right off the table, and all kinds of weird stuff happens.

672
00:40:28,941 --> 00:40:30,560
Scott: So this tower really makes things handy.

673
00:40:31,020 --> 00:40:34,091
Rym: Yeah, I basically bought the expansion only because it has this tower in it.

674
00:40:34,152 --> 00:40:36,420
Rym: I didn't really care what the tower expansion itself did.

675
00:40:36,660 --> 00:40:36,724
Scott: Mhm.

676
00:40:37,421 --> 00:40:42,737
Rym: And it changes the game in fundamental ways, but I think it's still a good game.

677
00:40:43,118 --> 00:40:43,640
Rym: I still win.

678
00:40:44,040 --> 00:40:49,539
Scott: It's a good game, but Inns and Cathedrals is still the same game, but just a little extra stuff.

679
00:40:50,740 --> 00:40:52,660
Scott: With the tower, it's a different game, I think.

680
00:40:52,920 --> 00:40:57,600
Rym: Very simply, the tower adds the ability to directly affect other players in a negative way.

681
00:40:58,100 --> 00:40:58,160
Scott: Mhm.

682
00:40:59,063 --> 00:41:03,619
Scott: You basically build these little towers instead of putting guys out if you want to.

683
00:41:04,981 --> 00:41:16,860
Rym: Instead of just place a tile and then either put a dude on it or not put a dude on it, you now have the option to, instead of putting a dude out, take a tower piece and put it on any tower-ready tile on the board.

684
00:41:17,340 --> 00:41:19,439
Rym: Not just the one you just played, but any of them.

685
00:41:20,861 --> 00:41:27,720
Rym: And if you put that tower down, anyone within x-spaces of that tower, you can take their dude off and keep him hostage.

686
00:41:28,141 --> 00:41:28,247
Scott: Mhm.

687
00:41:28,861 --> 00:41:32,700
Rym: And then if they take one of your dudes off, there's a prisoner swap and you both get your dudes back.

688
00:41:33,701 --> 00:41:39,420
Scott: So what this game does is it allows you to remove someone else's guy from the board.

689
00:41:39,580 --> 00:41:45,720
Scott: So if someone puts a guy in a castle and is going to score a hajillion points, you just put a little tower down and you take his guy right off the board.

690
00:41:46,500 --> 00:41:53,180
Scott: Of course, they can't put the tower just anywhere, they can only put it on the special tower tiles that come with the expansion, but there are a lot of them.

691
00:41:53,600 --> 00:41:59,260
Scott: And it's really hard to position things where they cannot possibly be towered or not easily be towered.

692
00:41:59,380 --> 00:42:07,900
Rym: Yup, thus you either have to finish things quickly, go in with other people, or try various strategies to keep people from screwing with your guys.

693
00:42:08,240 --> 00:42:10,060
Rym: It basically destroys the farming market.

694
00:42:10,700 --> 00:42:10,772
Rym: Mhm.

695
00:42:10,980 --> 00:42:13,480
Rym: Because farmers now are really, really vulnerable.

696
00:42:13,841 --> 00:42:15,079
Scott: And they're really hard to put out.

697
00:42:15,700 --> 00:42:20,600
Scott: Like, you can try to keep putting farmers out there, but someone will just tower them away.

698
00:42:20,680 --> 00:42:23,580
Scott: You have to really be clever to get the farmers into a good position.

699
00:42:23,660 --> 00:42:28,700
Rym: Of course, it's very balanced because any time you put a tower out, you had to not put a dude out.

700
00:42:29,342 --> 00:42:30,599
Rym: And putting a dude out is key.

701
00:42:31,020 --> 00:42:38,620
Scott: Of course, the thing is, in normal Carcassonne, you don't put a dude out, you put a dude out less than half the time you put a tile out.

702
00:42:38,800 --> 00:42:42,140
Scott: Because every turn you put a tile, but less than half the time you put a dude.

703
00:42:42,240 --> 00:42:43,607
Rym: See, that's your problem with Carcassonne.

704
00:42:43,788 --> 00:42:46,280
Rym: I almost always put a dude out, even if it's something crap.

705
00:42:47,501 --> 00:42:53,680
Rym: I have almost all my dudes out at all times, and I just cap off whatever they're on, even if they're little, and take the points, and then I put the dude back out.

706
00:42:54,281 --> 00:42:55,190
Scott: Oh, see, I don't do that.

707
00:42:55,251 --> 00:42:56,120
Scott: Maybe I'll try next time.

708
00:42:56,301 --> 00:42:57,018
Rym: That's how I win.

709
00:42:57,423 --> 00:42:59,359
Scott: Watch, I'll get punned next time when I try to do that.

710
00:43:03,011 --> 00:43:08,130
Scott: But yeah, whenever you would normally place a tile, but you wouldn't put a dude anyway, put a tower!

711
00:43:08,730 --> 00:43:12,690
Scott: Of course, you only have a limited number of towers, and the more players, the less towers you have.

712
00:43:13,111 --> 00:43:15,490
Rym: And every time you tower someone, you've got one of their guys hostage.

713
00:43:15,911 --> 00:43:18,810
Rym: So now, you're a target for them because they want their dude back.

714
00:43:19,130 --> 00:43:20,890
Scott: Yeah, it's kind of a great equalizer.

715
00:43:21,090 --> 00:43:26,690
Scott: If I keep screwing Rym, Rym has a big incentive to screw me instead of someone else.

716
00:43:26,890 --> 00:43:38,150
Scott: But, if I'm not way ahead of Rym in the scoring, he might not want to go after me, but he needs his guys back, and uhh, it's just an equalizing factor there, which is kind of good.

717
00:43:38,730 --> 00:43:41,810
Scott: Prevents people from just going after the guy in first place a whole bunch.

718
00:43:42,131 --> 00:43:43,905
Rym: Even though you tried to do that anyway, and it had no effect.

719
00:43:44,670 --> 00:43:46,526
Scott: I was in first place, you all went after me, and I lost.

720
00:43:46,566 --> 00:43:47,010
Scott: It worked great.

721
00:43:47,430 --> 00:43:48,969
Rym: No, we didn't use the towers to go after you.

722
00:43:49,591 --> 00:43:50,390
Scott: No, no, no, you didn't.

723
00:43:50,630 --> 00:43:52,825
Rym: We used the often-held strategy of "make a

724
00:43:52,866 --> 00:43:53,148
Rym: king.".

725
00:43:53,651 --> 00:43:54,054
Scott: Yup.

726
00:43:55,101 --> 00:43:56,470
Scott: The king of Carcassonne in the castle.

727
